[SN]TITLE[SN]
Anita Kapoor murder: Delivery driver Navin Mohan jailed for life

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
A delivery driver has been jailed for life for murdering a woman and dumping her body in a Buckinghamshire lay-by.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
Navin Mohan, 35, of no fixed address, was convicted of the murder of Anita Kapoor, whose body was found off the A413 near Gerrards Cross.
She went missing in the early hours of 23 June during a night out with her boyfriend, Reading Crown Court heard.
Judge Johanna Cutts said Mohan must serve 22 years before parole would be considered.
Ms Kapoor had been out with her boyfriend in Southall, but they had become separated.
He later told police he received a call from her phone and heard her begging for freedom.
Anita was heard saying, "please let me go, I won't say anything" before the line went dead.
After calling back repeatedly he called police and reported her missing.
Ms Kapoor's body was found at 08:30 by a member of the public. She was missing some of her personal effects, including her coat, trainers and mobile phone.
A post-mortem examination confirmed she had been strangled.
Mohan was caught on the evening of Wednesday, 24 June by police using mobile phone data, CCTV images and automatic number plate recognition.
The delivery driver was located, stopped in his Nissan Micra and arrested on suspicion of murder.
DNA evidence confirmed Ms Kapoor had been in his vehicle and he was charged with murder.
Det Chief Insp Kevin Brown said: "This was a vicious attack on a vulnerable woman.
"From the moment he was arrested by police until his conviction Mohan has denied responsibility for Anita's brutal murder, despite a weight of evidence against him."
Ms Kapoor's family said: "We have had to listen to details of how Anita was murdered - no-one can understand the impact this has had on us."
